							'To create a simple, type-safe auto-fill utility in a SvelteKit app using Supabase, you can follow these stepsn 1. First, make sure you have installed the necessary dependencies: `@supabase/supabase-js` and `svelte`.  2. Set up your Supabase client. In `src/lib/supabaseClient.js`, addn ```javascript import { createClient } from "@supabase/supabase-js";  const supabaseUrl = "your_supabase_url"; const supabaseKey = "your_supabase_key";  export const supabase = createClient(supabaseUrl, supabaseKey); ```  3. Create a `SearchItem` type. In `src/lib/types.ts`, addn ```typescript export interface SearchItem {   id: number;   name: string; } ```  4. Implement the search function using Supabase. In `src/lib/search.ts`, addn ```typescript import { supabase } from "./supabaseClient"; import type { SearchItem } from "./types";  export async function search(query: string): Promise<SearchItem[]> {   const { data, error } = await supabase     .from<SearchItem>("your_table_name")     .select("id, name")     .ilike("name", `%${query}%`)     .limit(10);    if (error) {     throw error;   }    return data || []; } ```  5. Create a Svelte component for the auto-fill search input. In `src/components/AutoFillSearchInput.svelte`, addn ```html <script lang="ts">   import { search } from "../lib/search";   import type { SearchItem } from "../lib/types";    let query = "";   let searchResults: SearchItem[] = [];   let isFocused = false;    async function handleInput() {     if (query.length > 2) {       searchResults = await search(query);     } else {       searchResults = [];     }   }    function handleFocus() {     isFocused = true;   }    function handleBlur() {     setTimeout(() => (isFocused = false), 150);   } </script>  <div class="search-container">   <input     type="text"     bind:value="{query}"     on:input="{handleInput}"     on:focus="{handleFocus}"     on:blur="{handleBlur}"     placeholder="Search"   />   {#if isFocused && searchResults.length}     <ul class="search-results">       {#each searchResults as result (result.id)}         <li>{result.name}</li>       {/each}     </ul>   {/if} </div>  <style>   .search-container {     position: relative;   }    .search-results {     position: absolute;     background: white;     list-style: none;     padding: 0;     margin: 0;     width: 100%;     border: 1px solid #ccc;     box-shadow: 0 2px 5px rgba(0, 0, 0, 0.1);   }    .search-results li {     padding: 10px;   }    .search-results li:hover {     background: #f0f0f0;     cursor: pointer;   } </style> ```  Now, you can use the `<AutoFillSearchInput>` component in your SvelteKit app. The auto-fill search input will show results fetched from your Supabase table, and it is type-safe using TypeScript.'
