							"In a time of Mughal and Afghan dominion, the enchanting Neelum Valley fell under the rule of the Bomba tribe's Muslim chieftains. Consequently, the significance of the pilgrimage to the sacred Sharada Peeth waned. However, the tide changed under Dogra rule when the benevolent Maharaja Gulab Singh restored the temple and granted the Gautheng Brahmans a monthly allowance, recognizing them as the temple's hereditary guardians.  Once again, the Kashmiri Pandit community thrived near the Sharada Peeth pilgrimage site, encompassing priests, traders, mystics, and their disciples. In a ritual of devotion, theologians would place their manuscripts before the goddess Sharada's idols, hoping for her divine blessings. The goddess would indicate her approval by leaving the writings untouched and her disapproval by disturbing the pages.  An annual fair would bring throngs of pilgrims to Shardi village, journeying through Kupwara in Kashmir to worship the goddess Sharada. Kashmiri Pandits held fast to the belief that the pilgrimage echoed Shandilya's journey and that bathing in the confluence of the Neelum River and Madhumati stream would absolve them of their sins.  In 1947, the revered Kashmiri saint, Swami Nand Lal Ji, relocated some stone idols to Tikker in Kupwara, and later to Devibal in Baramulla. However, the temple fell into disrepair after the Indo-Pakistani War of 1947-1948, which divided the princely state of Kashmir into the territories of Azad Kashmir and Jammu and Kashmir.  As a result, numerous Kashmiri Pandits migrated from Shardi to Jammu and Kashmir, and those unable to visit the shrine created alternative pilgrimage sites in Srinagar, Bandipore, and Gush. The echoes of the past still linger in the hearts of the devoted, longing to reconnect with their sacred Sharada Peeth."
