							'give me a tweetable summary of thisn _u2018It is this veneration and the daily religious and socio-religious services and ceremonies which have hitherto maintained discipline in the Hindu family and cemented it together. Their gradual extinction is tending to seriously disturb the harmony and happiness of the family among those who have advanced most on the Western path_u2026_u2026.Western civilisation on the other hand, takes but little heed of spiritual life and seeks to accomplish the well-being of man mainly_u2014if not solely_u2014by the gratification of his senses, by adding physical comforts, by multiplying his wants and desires. With us, the death of desire is the birth of happiness. With the Westerns, the satisfaction of desire is the chief, if not the only source of happiness as it is understood by them. Our sages have sought spiritual development at the expense of the animal, the Western scientists seek the expansion of the animal life taking little account of the spiritual_u2019,  As _u015ar_u012b.Sandeep Balakrishna says here.  If we are to stem the steady decline of our civilizational corpus, what would be the best model to begin with, how would we conceive its potential design, where would we make a creative intervention positively, in what manner would we try and bring our past glory back? Wherein people are not mere citizens but aesthetes of the highest order, where one_u2019s aesthetics does not merely serve epicurean tendencies but is based on the highest spiritual and philosophical ideals that our tradition holds as sacred. Where the connoisseur is also a patron and a performer. This idyllic scenario was put to test and implemented in Hyderabad last weekend to a rousing encore. From dance to music, puppetry to calligraphy, from hands on workshops to academic talks, every known creative fora was invited to participate, the theme being R_u0101m_u0101ya_u1e47a.  Why have yet another show on R_u0101m_u0101ya_u1e47a; IPS officer Hemant Pandey preempted this query by stating how R_u0101ma is a matter of anubhava i.e. experience and not anve_u1e63a_u1e47a i.e. research or academic study. Hence in these three days of indulging in R_u0101ma n_u0101ma (March 31st- April 2nd 2023 at the CCRT Auditorium, Hyderabad, Telangana) every activity was designed by Shankarananda Kalakshetra and Natyarambha with other associates, partners and sponsors, to evoke bhakti and _u015braddh_u0101 in the participants. Be it through R_u0101macaritram_u0101nas p_u0101_u1e6dha by Pandit Dilkash Bharti Sadanand Vishwakarma and Party all the way from Varanasi, be it the nagara sa_u1e43k_u012brtan_u0101 to the nearby R_u0101m_u0101layam in Hi-Tech city lead by Smt. T.K. Saroja and Sujatha, or through Thy_u0101gar_u0101ja _u0101r_u0101dhan_u0101 by singing his Pa_u00f1caratna k_u1e5bitis lead by Smt. Sweta Prasad, or whether it was with a fabulous Puppetry show by Smt. Anupama Hoskere of the B_u0101la K_u0101n_u1e0da and the exquisite kolam (muggu) by Smt. Hema Kannan, or via indulging in meditative garland making for p_u016bja by Shri. Rahul Teddy, everyone was absorbed in R_u0101ma.   Is R_u0101ma really a mary_u0101d_u0101 puru_u1e63ottama if he killed a woman, T_u0101_u1e6daka, or V_u0101li, hiding behind the trees, some may question. Supreme Court Advocate _u015ar_u012b. Sai Deepak, spoke on the concept of r_u0101jadharma and lessons from the R_u0101m_u0101ya_u1e47a which brought in thunderous claps and hoots from the audience. Smt. Ami Ganatra, who started off the R_u0101m_u0101m_u1e5bita session of talks by various experts, explained satisfactorily that R_u0101ma being the embodiment of dharma and ethical conduct, was bound by his duty to r_u0101jadharma; his kartavya as a king (even in exile) to protect people from adharma. An evil r_u0101k_u1e63as_u012b like T_u0101_u1e6daka who attacked without provocation and ate humans was not a dh_u0101rmika being, let alone a _u2018woman_u2019, a rapist like V_u0101li who forced himself on his brother_u2019s wife was not a dh_u0101rmika man. In fact getting rid of them was R_u0101ma_u2019s primary duty even as a k_u1e63atriya if not as a king. As Smt. Sudha Seshaiyyan reiterated the R_u0101m_u0101ya_u1e47a is not a story of a good hero versus an evil villain,  it is in fact a story about the sustenance of dharma. Sage Vasi_u1e63_u1e6dha and his father Da_u015baratha both teach R_u0101ma that it is not in the annexing of territories or going to war that makes a great king, but only by sustaining and upholding dharma is a great king made. Dr. Nagaraj Paturi provided more clarity by saying that reading the R_u0101m_u0101ya_u1e47a superficially or even academically, instead of indulging in our rituals and rites the way our ancestors did, we may conclude like Sheldon Pollock did that the R_u0101m_u0101ya_u1e47a is _u2018othering_u2019 and the Mah_u0101bh_u0101rata is _u2018brothering_u2019. Whereas the fact of the matter is that the R_u0101m_u0101ya_u1e47a has much more _u2018brotherhood_u2019 in it; be it R_u0101ma_u2019s filial bond with tribals, pak_u1e63_u012bs, r_u0101k_u1e63asas, vanav_u0101s_u012bs, or v_u0101naras. Here the cooperation is across the board and not limited to only humans!  A R_u0101m_u0101ya_u1e47a performance is an enactment of our sacred narrative, V_u0101lm_u012bki R_u0101m_u0101ya_u1e47a is not simply about the rasa (_u015bri_u1e43g_u0101ra being the main theme here) but also about extolling the gu_u1e47a, he added.   Chief Guest Hon_u2019ble Minister of Finance Smt. Nirmala Sitharaman extolled the epic R_u0101m_u0101ya_u1e47a, and the ideal that Lord R_u0101ma presents as a ruler and king to not just Indians but also to the rest of the South East Asian countries from Thailand to Vietnam. From the Ramakien of Thailand to Reamker of Cambodia to the Kakawin R_u0101m_u00e2ya_u1e47a of Indonesia, even in Laos and Vietnam, R_u0101m_u0101ya_u1e47a is a celebrated dance ballet that is performed with much love and reverence; a story that is as universal as it is personal in its idealism. _u201cIndian culture has been strongly influenced by the R_u0101m_u0101ya_u1e47a whether it is its old story telling, written texts, visual arts, dance, theatre, etc. R_u0101m_u0101ya_u1e47a has spread a wonderful fragrance in our daily lives._u201d she said.  Padmashri Dr. Ananda Shankar Jayanth_u2019s dance company presented Bh_u0101vay_u0101mi Raghur_u0101mam, which she choreographed to the Swathi Thirunal composition in a soul-stirring R_u0101gam_u0101lika, and was performed for the first time at the R_u0101m_u0101ya_u1e47a Kalpav_u1e5bik_u1e63am.The dance ballet itself was as much a scintillating showcase of the clear and crisp performance of the talented dancers of Shankarananda Kalakshetra as it was the thrilling choreography by Ananda ji. In many _u2018aha_u2019 moments, the ballet, which was visually splendorous, conveyed the very well known story in a unique manner. Be it the boat that Guha rows with R_u0101m_u0101, S_u012bt_u0101 and Lak_u1e63ma_u1e47a in tow, or the typical gait of Manthar_u0101, be it Hanum_u0101n or _u015a_u016brpa_u1e47akh_u0101 (both parts played adeptly by Srividya Sripathi), or R_u0101va_u1e47a carrying S_u012bt_u0101 away; with each set-piece, the freshness of the choreography stood out even while the Kalakshetra stamp was clearly visible. The form and lines were exact and in perfect coordination as is the hallmark of this hoary institution.   A point to be noted is that the n_u1e5btta in this piece took the narrative forward. Given that this ballet conveys the whole of the R_u0101m_u0101ya_u1e47a in under an hour, which is no easy task in itself, each time Ananda ji took over the na_u1e6d_u1e6d_u016bv_u0101ngam, the audience was presented with fast track feet literally taking us to the next sarga or k_u0101n_u1e0da in the story, very similar to K_u016bcip_u016b_u1e0di. Especially the building of the R_u0101ma Setu by Hanum_u0101n and other v_u0101naras was a treat to watch. When _u015a_u016brpa_u1e47akh_u0101 comes to pick a fight with R_u0101ma and Lak_u1e63ma_u1e47a, the various side plays happening simultaneously made the n_u0101_u1e6dya that much more enticing to experience, as the stage was made good use of, and one could pick and choose what and whom to concentrate on; a R_u0101ma and S_u012bta engaged in loving togetherness there, a Lak_u1e63ma_u1e47a engaged in chores and sharpening his arrows here. The thoughtful choreography made use of the stage and space with dexterity.   It would have been good to have men play some parts in this ballet, but for this we need more men to take up the classical arts, especially dance. If they did, certain roles could be played by men without women having to resort to playing both parts. Unlike K_u016bcip_u016b_u1e0di where men played women_u2019s parts in olden days, today we have women playing male parts due to the dearth of men taking up classical dance and the arts in large numbers, and with dedication. Also unlike the other dance form Vil_u0101s_u012bni N_u0101_u1e6dyam, the devad_u0101si dance of the Telugu states (or even K_u016b_u1e0diya_u1e6d_u1e6dam from Kerala), there was not much scope for detailed intricate abhinaya in this particular dance-drama.  As expected of classical arts of the bh_u0101rat_u012bya jn_u0101na parampar_u0101, the dance ballet transported rasik_u0101s to subtle realms of the R_u0101m_u0101ya_u1e47a, connecting them to navarasas through n_u0101_u1e6dya and sang_u012bta. A person moved by such aesthetics and wanting to preserve it, to be a patron, is a n_u0101garika in the truest sense (Harsha V. Dehejia. The Advaita in Art), a civilised and refined person capable of letting go of the grossly mundane for the spiritually abstract, even while staunchly protecting and propagating what is available.   Indian Aesthetics, with its _u2018age-old_u2019 canons of rasa, dhvani, aucitya, and vakrokti has no significant role to play in the modern and post-modern world of literary criticism. This is an unfound objection. Every theory of art appreciation connected with expression (vakrokti), suggestion (dhvani), impression (aucitya) and experience (rasa)_u2014developed by any school of thought at any point in time_u2014finds its philosophical and applicational completion in the canons of Indian Aesthetics. The champions of modernity are preoccupied with socio-political and geo-cultural implications of Aesthetics and care little for pure art.  Pure art was made evident in the Hari Kath_u0101 rendition by Vid. Vishakha Hari in her navarasa R_u0101m_u0101ya_u1e47a. With a mixture of compositions in Telugu, Marathi, Tamizh and Sanskrit, she took a specific incident from the R_u0101m_u0101ya_u1e47a to evoke a particular rasa. For example the h_u0101sya rasa is not usually associated with the R_u0101m_u0101ya_u1e47a, but there are many incidents including the antics of the v_u0101naras which evoke laughter in us. All this was sung in specific r_u0101gas associated with each rasa. Blessed by M_u0101 Sarasvat_u012b, Vishakha ji regaled everyone with her erudition, her stories, and her felicity with the svaras. '
