					content: {
						content_type: 'text',
						parts: [
							"Creating a design system documentation is essential for maintaining a consistent brand and website experience. Here's an outline to help you put together your design system documentationn 1. Introduction    - Briefly explain the purpose of the design system and how it will benefit your brand and website.  2. Brand Colors    - Primary Colors: List your primary brand colors, along with their color codes (e.g., HEX, RGB, and CMYK) and any associated meanings or emotions.    - Secondary Colors: List any secondary colors that complement the primary colors and provide their color codes as well.    - Tertiary Colors: If applicable, list tertiary colors for specific use cases, with their color codes.    - Color Usage: Explain the appropriate use of colors across different elements like backgrounds, text, buttons, and icons.  3. Brand Logos    - Logo Variations: Display all logo versions, including full color, monochrome, and inverted color variations.    - Logo Sizes: Specify the standard sizes for each logo version and how they should be scaled for various platforms and devices.    - Logo Spacing: Explain the minimum clear space around the logo to ensure visibility and impact.    - Logo Usage: Provide guidelines on how and where to use each logo version, along with any restrictions or prohibited uses.  4. Brand Typography    - Primary Typeface: Identify the primary typeface used for headings, subheadings, and body text.    - Secondary Typeface: If applicable, specify a secondary typeface for specific use cases, such as quotes or callouts.    - Font Sizes: Define the standard font sizes for various text elements (e.g., headings, subheadings, body text, captions, etc.).    - Font Weights: Specify the appropriate font weights for different text elements, such as bold, regular, or light.    - Font Usage: Explain how typography should be used to maintain visual hierarchy and readability.  5. Key Visuals    - Photography: Describe the style and subject matter of the images that represent your brand, along with guidelines for composition, lighting, and color treatment.    - Illustrations: Explain the preferred illustration style and how it should be used to complement your brand identity.    - Iconography: Provide examples of icons that follow your brand's visual language, and explain how to use them effectively.    - Data Visualization: Offer guidelines for presenting data in charts, graphs, and infographics to ensure consistency and clarity.  6. UI Components (if applicable)    - Provide examples of common UI elements such as buttons, input fields, and navigation menus, showcasing how they should be styled to align with your brand.  7. Design Templates    - Include examples of templates for various marketing materials, such as social media posts, email newsletters, and print collateral.  8. Conclusion    - Summarize the key takeaways and emphasize the importance of adhering to the design system for a consistent brand experience.  Remember to keep your documentation updated as your brand evolves, and make it accessible to all team members involved in creating content for your brand and website."
						]
					},
