							"Yes, your example should work correctly with the declared variables `$scaler` and `$scalerlow`. However, there is a more efficient and cleaner way to achieve the same effect using SASS mixins and a loop. Here's an example of how you can rewrite your SASS code more efficientlyn ```scss $scaler: 1.25; $scalerlow: 1.2;  @mixin heading-sizes($level, $font-size) {   @if $level == 1 {     font-size: $font-size;   } @else {     font-size: $font-size * $scalerlow;     @include heading-sizes($level - 1, $font-size * $scaler);   } }  .scaled {   p, h6, h5, h4, h3, small, cite, li, pre {     margin: 0 0 var(--long-c) 0;   }   @media screen and (min-width: 1024px) {     p {       font-size: 1vw;     }     @for $i from 3 through 6 {       h#{$i} {         @include heading-sizes($i - 2, 1vw * $scaler);       }     }   } } ```  In this example, we use a mixin called `heading-sizes` to handle the font sizing logic. This mixin takes two arguments, `$level` and `$font-size`. The `$level` variable determines how many times the font size will be multiplied by the `$scaler` and `$scalerlow` variables. The mixin uses recursion to calculate the final font size.  We also use a SASS `@for` loop to apply the mixin to each heading element (`h3` through `h6`). This loop generates the heading element selectors and includes the mixin with the appropriate level.  This approach makes your code more maintainable and easier to read, as the logic for the font scaling is encapsulated within the mixin."
