							"To run an animation in SvelteKit on both `click` and `keydown` events, you can use the `use` directive to create a reusable animation function and call it on both events.  Here's an examplen ```html <script>   import { use } from 'svelte';      function animate() {     // your animation logic here   }      const handleClick = () => {     use(animate)();   };      const handleKeyDown = (event) => {     if (event.key === 'Enter' || event.key === ' ') {       use(animate)();     }   }; </script>  <button on:click={handleClick} on:keydown={handleKeyDown}>Click or press enter/space</button> ```  In this example, the `animate` function is defined outside of the event handlers so that it can be reused on both `click` and `keydown` events. The `use` directive is used to run the animation function whenever the event handlers are triggered.  In the `handleClick` function, the `animate` function is called directly. In the `handleKeyDown` function, the `animate` function is called only if the `Enter` or `Space` keys are pressed, which are commonly used as alternative keys for clicking buttons.  Finally, both the `click` and `keydown` events are added to the button element with the appropriate event handlers to trigger the animation."
