							'Yes, you can set a root font size using CSS, which is typically set to 16px by default.   To set a custom root font size, you can add the following CSS to the `html` elementn ```css html {   font-size: 16px; /* replace 16px with your desired root font size */ } ```  Once you have set the root font size, you can use `rem` units to size your fonts relative to the root font size, making them responsive to changes in the root font size.  For example, if you want to set the font size of a `h1` element to be 2.5 times the root font size, you can use the following CSSn ```css h1 {   font-size: 2.5rem; } ```  This will set the font size of the `h1` element to be 2.5 times the root font size, which will adjust automatically if you change the root font size.'
