							"There are a few options you can consider when using data from multiple functions on a single SvelteKit pagen 1. Put all the code in the <script> tag in +page.svelte itselfnYou can certainly do this, but it may result in a lot of code in one file, which can become difficult to manage as your codebase grows.  2. Do all these in +page.server.tsnThis is another option, but it may not be the most efficient. If you do all the data fetching on the server side, the page will need to wait for all the data to be fetched before it can be rendered. This can result in longer loading times, especially if the data being fetched is large.  3. Use an API/supabase +server.ts file where you fetch all data, and from there get it to the pagesnThis is the recommended approach. You can create an API route in your +server.ts file that fetches all the data you need and returns it as JSON. You can then call this API from your SvelteKit page to get the data you need. This allows you to separate your data fetching logic from your page component, which makes it easier to manage and scale.  Here's an example of how you can create an API route in your +server.ts file to fetch the data you needn ```typescript import { supabase } from '$lib/supabaseClient'; import type { Request } from '@sveltejs/kit';  export async function get(request: Request) {   const [updateOne, latest, books, mrdanga, kavita, iks, other] = await Promise.all([     updateOne(),     Latest(),     getBooks(),     getMrdanga(),     getKavita(),     getIKS(),     getOther()   ]);    return {     body: {       updateOne,       latest,       books,       mrdanga,       kavita,       iks,       other     }   }; }  async function updateOne() {   // fetch data from supabase }  async function Latest() {   // fetch data }  async function getBooks() {   // fetch data }  async function getMrdanga() {   // fetch data }  async function getKavita() {   // fetch data }  async function getIKS() {   // fetch data }  async function getOther() {   // fetch data } ```  In your SvelteKit page component, you can then fetch the data from the API using the `fetch` functionn ```typescript <script>   let data;    async function fetchData() {     const res = await fetch('/api/my-data');     data = await res.json();   }    fetchData(); </script> ```   Note that you will need to adjust the `fetch` URL to match the name of your API route and any parameters you need to pass. Additionally, you will need to adjust the `get` function in your +server.ts file to match the data fetching functions you need."
