							"If you are seeing an error in VS Code when using a semicolon (`;`) in Sass, it's possible that there is an issue with your configuration or syntax. Here are a few things to checkn 1. Make sure you are using the correct file extension for your Sass file. Sass files can have either a `.scss` or `.sass` extension. If you are using the `.sass` syntax, you should not use semicolons to terminate declarations.  2. Check your syntax to make sure that you are using semicolons correctly. In Sass, semicolons are used to terminate declarations, but not at the end of a block. For examplen ``` // Correct usagen$color-strong: #B0413E; .my-element {   color: $color-strong; }  // Incorrect usagen$color-strong: #B0413E; .my-element {   color: $color-strong; }; ```  Note that in the incorrect usage, there is a semicolon after the closing brace of the `.my-element` block, which is not needed.  3. Check your VS Code extensions to make sure that there are no conflicts or errors. If you have extensions that affect the syntax highlighting or linting of your Sass files, they could be causing issues with semicolons.  If you're still having trouble, you may want to try using a Sass compiler like node-sass or sass-loader to compile your Sass code. These tools can help catch syntax errors and provide more detailed error messages."
