							"In Sass, you can also use the double-slash (`//`) notation to write single-line comments like in CSS. However, Sass also supports multi-line comments, which can be useful for adding longer descriptions or notes. Here's how to write comments in Sassn 1. Single-line comments: To write a single-line comment in Sass, you can use the double-slash (`//`) notation just like in CSS. Anything after the `//` will be ignored by the Sass compiler.  ``` // This is a Sass file $color-strong: #B0413E; // Define a color variable .my-element {   color: $color-strong; } ```  2. Multi-line comments: To write a multi-line comment in Sass, you can use the `/*  */` notation. Anything between the opening `/*` and closing `*/` will be ignored by the Sass compiler.  ``` /* This is a Sass file    It defines some color variables */  $color-strong: #B0413E; // Define a strong color $color-soft: #C5C5C5;   // Define a soft color  .my-strong-element {   color: $color-strong; }  .my-soft-element {   color: $color-soft; } ```  Note that Sass comments can span multiple lines and can be nested within other comments, which can be useful for organizing and documenting your code."
