							'  1. To select the specific child of a div class that you hover on, you can use the :hover pseudo-class selector and the child selector (>). For example, if you have a div with the class "parent" and you want to style its second child when it is hovered over, you can use the following CSS rulen ``` .parent:hover > :nth-child(2) {   /* styles for the second child of .parent when it is hovered over */ } ```  The `:nth-child(2)` selector selects the second child element of `.parent`. The `>` selector selects only direct child elements of `.parent`, so it ensures that the rule only applies to the second child of `.parent` and not any deeper descendants.  2. To select all other children of a div class except the one you are hovering on, you can use the :not() and :hover pseudo-class selectors. For example, if you have a div with the class "parent" and you want to style all of its children except the one that is currently being hovered over, you can use the following CSS rulen ``` .parent:hover > *:not(:hover) {   /* styles for all children of .parent except the one being hovered over */ } ```  The `*` selector selects all child elements of `.parent`. The `:not(:hover)` selector excludes any child elements that are currently being hovered over. The `>` selector ensures that the rule only applies to direct child elements of `.parent`.'
