							"You can join tables A and B on the `words` column and include the `meanings` column from table B in the query. Here's an example queryn ```sql SELECT A.words, B.meanings FROM A JOIN B ON A.words = B.words; ```  This query uses the `JOIN` keyword to join tables A and B on the `words` column. The `ON` keyword specifies the condition for the join, which is that the `words` column in A matches the `words` column in B.   The `SELECT` statement selects the `words` column from table A and the `meanings` column from table B, and returns them in the result set.  This query will only return rows where there is a match between the `words` columns in both tables. If you want to include all rows from table A, even if there is no match in table B, you can use a `LEFT JOIN` insteadn ```sql SELECT A.words, B.meanings FROM A LEFT JOIN B ON A.words = B.words; ```  This query will return all rows from table A, and the `meanings` column from table B will be `NULL` for rows where there is no match."
